spanGrp.span: Ndoe aram na nd'e / k'a / jap lwa ns'et / ndoe liit.
Behold, (here) is a story about the little bush animals and the lion.
D. tells a folktale about the rabbit and the lion.
Liit / a toe long jap lwa yi dip nd'n s'et.
The lion, (it was him who was) the chief of all the small animals in the bush.
Liit d'e d'i ndoe mat ji / ndoe jap ji.
The lion was there with his wife and his children.
Sai ndoe la liit / gok / muut.
Then a child of the lion became sick, (and it) died.
D'emde lwa moenan / wul goeme goeme t'ong doe tal liit / t'ong buk yok.
The other big animals arrived one (by) one, (and they) would greet the lion here, (they) would return home again.
Jap lwa moed'yen ns'et nnoe zak.
These small animals of the bush, (they) too.
Mep yi: "Poe du men du tal / long dwen."
They said: "Let them go (and) greet their chief."
Ko da yake mep man / goefe liit d'e t'ong haar mep yi.
Even though they know that the lion is eating them.
Amma mep mang boezung / de-goe men goe-- / goe tal ni / goe bi goet'a goe ni / goe muut la muk.
But they took courage to go and--, and greet him with the thing that befell him, with the death of his child.
Mep p-- / p'at / doe t'el k'ek sek / mep t'wot.
They--, went out, (they) gathered themselves together here, they sat.
Mep rang bi goepe mep t'ong men goe k'wal ndoe liit.
They thought (about) the thing that they would go and talk with the lion.
Gya goefe mep t'ong mang goe wakaam / de-goe nyok rwo nlu liit.
The song that they would sing on the way in order to return home (and) enter the house of the lion.
Mep [??] / yin: "T'ong du men du goe k'wal a k'wal / ndoe bi mou."
They (***), (they) said: "They should not just go and talk a talk about anything."
"T'ong du k'wal a k'a goepe / a mmoe sa toe muut nyang yi goe mang ndoe dwen / ba yi yool goe mang a la liit / goepe ni toe long dwen yi."
"They would talk about (the thing) that, what (is it that) made death refuse to take one of them, so that (death) returned (instead and) rose and took the child of the lion, who is their chief."
Mep t'wot sh-- / shin / nye / d'e nnoe.
They sat (and) did--, did the word, this talk.
Mep sh-- / yl p'at de-goe nmen.
They did--, (they) rose (and) went out to go.
Sai fan / d'in t'ong d'i goet'oor k'oeleng bi goek'wal mep.
Then the rabbit, (he) had sat there by the side (and) had listened (to) the thing they talked (about).
Yin: "Nwa t'ong men a de-goe nk'wal a k'wal nnoe ndoe liit a?"
(He) said: "Would they go to talk this talk to the lion?"
Yin: "To a nwa t'ong tang a k'wal de-goe nloe nk'ek nwa."
(He) said: "Okay, they would search (for) trouble to put on their heads."
"A bi mmoe weel nwa toe poenoe nwa k'wal k'wal ndoe ni yi?"
"What disturbs them like this, (so that) they (would) talk (this) talk to him (i.e., to the lion)?"
"Na liit nnoe a bi goehaar dwen o?"
"See, this lion is the thing that eats them, isn't he?"
"Liit t'ong tu ko-la goenang b'ak haar."
"The lion would kill every little one here (and) eat (it)."
"De nwa goe men goe k'wal iri k'wal nd'ennoe yi ndoe ni wa?"
"So that they should go (and) should talk this existing kind of talk with him, right?"
Yin: "Nwa t'ong men goe k'wal a poenoe."
(He) said: "They would go (and) should talk like this."
"Avu la liit muut nd'ong / avu la kung muut nd'ong / bi goehaal gulum muut nd'ong."
"Hey, the child of the lion has died, (this is) being good, hey, the child of the leopard has died, (this is) being good, the thing that eats people has died, (this is) being good."

According to A., the [n-] in [nd'ong] was only inserted to fit the music - in order speech it would be [la liit muut d'ong]. The [l] in [haal] and [gulum] is considered to be the speech of children or animals (in folktales).
"Avu la liit muut nd'ong / avu la kung muut nd'ong / bi goehaal gulum muut nd'ong."
"Hey, the child of the lion has died, (this is) being good, hey, the child of the leopard has died, (this is) being good, the thing that eats people has died, (this is) being good."
"Nwa la men / de ni goe man yi goepe ni d'e t'ong haar dwen yi nd'n s'et."
"When they go, so that he should know that he (is the one who) is eating them in the bush."
They, however, they were just stupid.
They listened to the voice of the rabbit.
Goe gya mpe mep shyang mep kt.
With a song in their mouths (that) just pleased them.
Mp'ung yool dung d'yem goede k'ek mep.
Dust rose (and) moved to and fro (and) stood (in a cloud) following them.
Mep mang gya yok wul nlu liit.
They sang the song (and) returned back (and) arrived at the house of the lion.
"Avu la liit muut nd'ong / avu la kung muut nd'ong / bi goehaal gulum muut nd'ong."
"Hey, the child of the lion has died, (this is) being good, hey, the child of the leopard has died, (this is) being good, the thing that eats people has died, (this is) being good."
Mep k'wal kt t'ong b'ep nk'wal kt.
They just talked (and they) would just repeat (the) talking.
Mat liit p'et / doe d'yem / zem de-goe nyool b'yaal.
The wife of the lion came out, (she) stood here, (she) wanted to rise (in) anger.
Mis muk / liit yin: / "Pa goe d'yem nkyem."
Her husband, the lion, said: "She should wait first."
"B'ep du k'oeleng bi goed'e mep t'ong k'wal yi."
"They (should) hear again the thing that they are talking (about)."
They arranged (themselves) again, (and they) listened attentively.
Mep k'oeleng / bi goek'wal mep / toed'ong nt'it / lat.
They heard the thing that they talked (about), (they heard it) clearly, very much (so), (until it) had ended.
Mep doe tarap / k'ek jap lwa ns'et nnoe.
They broke here the heads of all these little animals of the bush.
Mep two kt t'ong tar kwan.
They just killed (them and) would tear (them) apart (and) throw (them) away.
Two kt t'ong tar kwan d'emde swo.
(They) just killed (them and) would tear (them) apart (and) throw (them) away, others ran (away).
Swo [??] nkwa mep marap t'oerep ns'et.
(They) ran (***) away, they died (and) lay in the bush.
Sai fan swar kt muut bi ji.
Then the rabbit just laughed (and nearly) died (of laughter) (in) his own way.
Yir kt ba kt d'oot goe-goe mang / yim / uh / f'im kr.
(He) just turned (and) just returned (and was) quiet and eventually took leaves, uh, cotton of the silk cotton tree.
(He) submerged (it) in water (and put it) on his head.
(He) fetched water (and) poured (it) there on top.
D'e t'ong sam yi nyit muk goebi yitmahoe.
(It) was running down his face like tears.
A (10/12/99) suggests that [goebi yitmahoe yi] would be better.
Wa kt wa wul t'ong mpe lu liit.
(He) just returned, (he) returned (and) arrived (and) sat at the door of the lion.
"A bi mmoe shin muut nnoe toe?"
"A nd'ang de muut nyang goe mang gwen d'ongya?"
"How (come) that death refused to take those of little animals (lit. "good-to-catch")?"
"A nd'ang de muut nyang goe mang gwen paap?"
"How (come) that death refused to take those of the antelope?"
"A nd'ang de muut nyang goe mang gwen fan?"
"How (come) that death refused to take those of the rabbit?"
"Muut yi yool goe t'a a nk'a la liit / goepe ni toe nda dwen toe / goepe ni toe long dwen toe ns'et."
"So that death rose (instead) and fell on the child of the lion, who is their father, who is their chief in the bush."
"T'ong ji b'oot mou / t'ong ji b'oot mou."
"He wouldn't be able (to stand it), he wouldn't be able (to stand it)."
"T'ong ji b'oot mou / t'ong ji b'oot mou."
"He wouldn't be able (to stand it), he wouldn't be able (to stand it)."
Gwen liit yl / hai. "Gwa goe d'ok. Gwa goe d'ok. Kede gwa boemang wal de-goe nma goe k'oom ba. Gwa goe d'ok kt. Gwa goe shin. Gwa goe moor. Gwa goe d'ok."
The lions rose, hey. "He should be silent. He should be silent. He shouldn't cry to surpass (his) strength. He should just be silent. He should do (it). He should be patient. He should be silent."
Yin / ni yin: / "Goeshir muk d'e nnang?"
(He) said, he said: "Where is his grave?"
Yin: "Ji zem de-goe maan goe p'en ni nnoe dip." Mep yin: "Kwai / gwa goe moor / goe t'a goe t'ong."
(He) said: "He wants to go and remove him all." They said: "No, he should be patient, (he) should sit down."
They received the rabbit (and) sat (him) down.
Ase me / a hangoed'e kalfel / goerok.
Surprose, (it was) water (with) the froth of beer, sweet (water).
The rabbit received the water behind (the house to wash himself).
Maan goe nak hangoed'e d'e nsn.
(He) went and fetched the water (and) poured (it) over his body.
Kat hangoed'e hok rok mpe muk.
(He) found (that) the water was sweet in his mouth.
D. has used [nak] 'drip' in place of [rok] in his original transcript.
Ba doe kat mep yin: / "Ai / hangoed'e hok kwan nyil."
(He) returned (and) found them here (and) said: "Hey, the water has spilled on the ground."
Mep nak nde poe ni zak-yit.
They fetched some more (and) gave (it to) him again.
Mang d'emgoed'e kyoklok / p'iring nsek muk.
(He) took the small rest, (and he) turned (it) over his body.
Yir p'et / ba doe t'a t'ong.
(He) turned (and) went out, (he) returned (and) sat down here.
Mep shin s'oe poe ni s'oe.
They made food (and) gave (it to) him (and he) ate.
"B'it la d'a lin / de ji wa yi."
"When tomorrow dawns, so that he (would) return home."
Pe ngong / mep poe pin nfan wa goe t'a t'o.
When (it was) night, they gave a hut to the rabbit (and he) returned back and lay down.
A (14/12/99): better to say [pe la ngong] or [pe wa ngong]
Goepe fan na mep saam lat / fan yool p'et nk'ong pin / pe goed'e goeshir hok.
When the rabbit saw (that) they had fallen asleep, the rabbit rose (and) went out behind the hut, (to) the place where there was the grave.
(He) started to dog the grave (lit., he fell on the grave to dig).
(He) dug the grave, (he) would dug the grave.
Sai liit hok p'et doe kat ni.
Then the lion came out (and) found him here.
"A nd'ang gwa t'ong hok k'a goeshir ngonghoe e?"
"How (come that) he would dig on the grave during the night?"
Yin: "T'yak ji rang nye toe ma goe k'oom yi."
(He) said: "His heart thinks the things (so that it) surpasses (his) strength."
"Ji zem bi ji a de-goe np'en ni de ji / de ji ru t'uun yi goede k'a muk / de ji t'oerep goeshak ndoe ni."
"He wants (in) his own wat to remove him, so that he, so that he enters (into) the hole following him, so that he lies together with him."
A (14/12/99) suggests [de du goe t'oerep yi sek shak] as being a better alternative.
"The death hurts very much in his body."
Liit yin: "To gwa goe shin hak'uri."
The lion said: "Okay, he should remain patient."
"Gwa goe moor goe ba goe t'o."
"He should be patient (and) return (and) lie (i.e., sleep)."
Sai ndoe goepe fan / mong mep saam / marap sosai / nt'it / nkyem fan yool yi doe hok / la liit nnoe.
Then some (time passed) when the rabbit studied them closely (and they) slept thoroughly (like they) had died, before the rabbit (would) rise (and) dig here (at) this child of the lion.
Goepe hok / la liit nnoe kt / har goe kat pe goed'e k'um hok / p'en / k'um hok / ngong hok / yool su wa bi muk.

When (he) just dug (at) this child of the lion, until (he) should find the place where there is the corpse, (he) removed (it), the corpse, during the night, (and he) rose (and) ran (and) returned home (in) his own way.
Liit p'et d'em mb'itlung de-goe doe na fan hok kat fan ba.
The lion went out now in the morning to see the rabbit here (but he) didn't find the rabbit.
Mep men goe goeshir mep kat / hok goeshir de p'en la / wa kam.
They went to the place of the grave (and) they found (that he) had dug the grave so that (he) removed (the body), (and) he had returned home.
Mep p'at yi leng / tang pe goed'e fan.
So they went out (and) moved around (and) searched (for) the place where the rabbit was.
Mep yok doe / doe kat ni / d'a wa doe nlu.
They returned home (and) came, (they) found him here, when (he) had returned home (and) came to the house.
They, too, returned back (to the rabbit's house) (and) arrived.
Mep t'an ni de-goe ndoe ya.
They pursued him to catch (him) here.
Fan p'aar goe-goe t'a nd'n me.
The rabbit jumped and eventually fell into a granary.
Liit zem de-goe nrp me hok.
The lion wanted to demolish the granary.
Fan mang bi goed'e nd'n / me nnoe.
The rabbit took the things that were inside this granary.
La lyak / goet'eng poenoe / mpe me / liit lap lyak nk'ong ji.
When (he) threw (the things) up like this, through the opening of the granary, the lion received (them and) threw (them) behind him.
La mang goesoe lang mpe me / liit lap lyak nk'ong ji.
When (he) took this one (and) hung (it) at the opening of the granary, the lion received (it and) threw (it) behind him.
Mang gwen / d'a goet'wot d'i / liit lap lyak nk'ong ji.
(He) took those calabashes that sat thre, the lion received (them and) threw (them) behind him.
Sai ru kt t'o nd'n la bang.
Then (he) just entered (and) lay inside a little calabash.
Goepe t'o nd'n bang lat / b'iring kt haan mpe me. Goepe liit lap / bang hok / lyak nk'ong ji maan goe-goe p'yan goe fan nd'n. Fan p'et / yool su zak-yit.

When (he) lied in the calabash, (he) just rolled (and) ascended through the opening of the granary. When the lion received the calabash, (he) threw (it) behind him (and it) went and eventually broke with the rabbit inside. The rabbit went out, (he) rose (and) ran again.
Mep yin mep yi: "Ai fan nlang nang-panang / fan wa kam."
They said, they said: "Hey, behold, there over there the rabbit is moving, the rabbit has returned home."
Fan ru maan doe kat k'um.
The rabbit entered (and) went (and) found here a corpse.
Lwa goepe t'o wam shin nyit poezek poezek sek.
An animal that lay (and) has become rotten (and) has worms, (moving) - poezek poezek - their bodies.
Fan mang / k'aramshim fan hok / uh / bi wam hok / k'oon nk'a ji.
The rabbit took the skin of the rabbit, uh, the rotten thing, (and he) put (it) face down over his head.
Goepe goek'oon nk'a ji / t'ong d'em / goe wakaam goepe liit d'e nt'an ni yi.
When, when he had put (it) over (his) head, (he) sat now on the road where the lion was pursuing him.
Liit wa wul doe kat / bi nnoe goet'ong.
The lion returned back (and) arrived (and) found here this thing that sat.
The thing disgusted the lion in his body.
The lion moved aside (and) stood by the side.
Sai mep / sai bi hok / tal kt.
Then they, then the thing just greeted (them).
Yin: "Gwa t'ong maan a nnanghoe a?"
Sai liit yin: "Ji d'e t'ong ji tang a fan."
Then the lion said: "He is searching (for) the rabbit."
"Dam k'yak ji sosai." Yin: "Ji zem de-goe ntu ni."
"(He) had upset him very much." (He) said: "He wants to kill him."
Sai bi hok k'wal kt ndoe liit yin: / "Oh."
Then the thing just talked to the lion (and) said: "Oh."
"D'in la goe zem d'e noe / d'in t'ong goe bi fan ba."
"If you would accept my advice, you wouldn't follow the rabbit."
"Nyegoepe goe na fan / dok shin bi goedam k'yak noe poenoe. Moe t'an ni de-goe ntu."
"Because, you see, the rabbit has done something in the past that upset me like this. We pursued him to kill (him)."
"Sai mang s'a muk nin nyit noe."
"Then (he) took his hand (and) pointed (it) at my face."
"Goepe nin s'a muk nyit noe lat / hen wam yi t'onghoe."
"When (he) had pointed his hand at my face, so I became rotten (and now) sit (like this)."
"Ko hen la mang s'a noe zak nin nyit goe / sa ba goe / t'ong goe wam zak / kat hen la nin s'a noe nyit goe."
"Maybe if I also take my hand (and) point (it) at your face, (it would) make (it that) you return (and that) you would become rotten, too, maybe if I point my hand at your face."
Liit k'oeleng poenoennoe / na liit yool / yir yit ji / yool su p'et wa nlu.
The lion heard (it) like this, (we) saw the lion (and he) rose, (he) turned his face, (he) rose (and) ran (and) went out (and) returned home to (his) house.
T'ong ji k'ara ji tang pe goed'e fan zak-yit mou.
He would never again search (for) the place where the rabbit is.
The rabbit went out now (in) his own way.
Goepe k'oeleng pe na liit su lat / fan p'et.
When (he) heard, when (he) saw (that) the lion had run away, the rabbit went out.
Goedoe mang yit nni / liit goe na / fan nni.
When (he) showed his face here to him, the lion should see the rabbit with it.
Liit yo / sh'yan d'yem / goe su.
The lion rose, (he) met (him and) stood, and (then he) ran.
The rabbit pursued him on purpose.
Ba bi ji goe t'a t'ong swar yi.
(He) returned (in) his own way and sat down so that (he) laughed.
